04050nam a22006735i 9783110759853DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20242024gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107598537 a10.1515/97831107598532doi  a(DE-B1597)589906  a(OCoLC)1417742367  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE1 aWilk, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn on the Joke: The Ethics of Humor and Comedy /cThomas Wilk, Steven Gimbel. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (X, 144 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDe Gruyter Studies in Philosophy of Humor ,x2699-3481 ;v400tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIntroduction. The Need for a Better Account of Joke Ethics -- tChapter 1: Das Capital: Joke Capital and Where to Get It -- tChapter 2: You Know Me Better Than That: Joking with Friends -- tChapter 3: We Hardly Knew Ye: Joking with Strangers -- tChapter 4: From Open Mics to Open Minds: Joking on Stage -- tChapter 5: Hey Boss, That’s Pretty Funny: Joking with Power -- tChapter 6: Putting the “Twit” in Twitter: Virtual Jokes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWho is morally permitted to tell jokes about Jews? Poles? Women? Only those in the group? Only those who would be punching up? Anyone, since they are just jokes? All of the standard approaches are too broad or too narrow. In on the Joke provides a more sophisticated approach according to which each person possesses "joke capital" that can serve as "comic insurance" covering certain jokes in certain contexts. When Bob tells a joke about Jews, we can never know exactly what Bob is intending since we cannot see inside Bob’s mind. But we could reasonably infer, if we knew Bob himself was Jewish, if he worked tirelessly for Jewish causes, or was a card-carrying Neo-Nazi. Each would affect his joke capital, and, in certain circumstances, we would have a moral standing to demand to see his ledger to see how much joke capital he had with respect to Jews. The permissibility of that joke depends upon four factors: the joke, the teller of the joke, the audience, and the setting. The view developed in In on the Joke is the only view that clearly explains how each of these components work together in an integrated, effective ethic of humor.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEthik. 4aGesellschaftsvertrag. 4aHumor. 4aWitze.  aHumor.  aethics.  ajokes.  asocial contract.1 aGimbel, Steven, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2024 Part 1z97831113321920 cEPUBz97831107600260 cprintz978311075975440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311075985340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110759853423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110759853/original  a978-3-11-133219-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2024 Part 1b2024  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles